            <p>The article aims to provide an overview of current regulatory barriers to the implementation of energy communities and P2P energy trading within the context of the EU regulation. The article starts by stating the need for Energy Communities, which is followed by a brief overview of the regulatory landscape and an overview of the NRG2Peer project. This is followed by the main section, which addresses four dimensions of the readiness level framework stated in the introduction and some broad key challenges or barriers to implementation. Finally, the article finishes by providing an overview of the current NRG2PEER roadmap and Advisory app.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> While the article provides a brief overview of the regulatory landscape of Energy Communities, it is not clear what the article's main purpose is and should be specifically outlined in the abstract and in the introduction.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the introduction/background section, an overview of the current regulatory landscape is given, however it would be beneficial also to include how Citizen Energy Communities differ from Renewable Energy Communities and why the focus here is explicitly on RECs. Further, RED II has defined the term "Peer-to-peer trading of renewable energy" which could be mentioned as it provides guidance for Member States for their national implementation of the directive. The introduction also provides a broad overview of the Readiness Level Framework used in this study as well as the different dimensions, however information or reference needs to be given for the specifics of the Readiness Level Framework, which is used further in the next section. Additionally, the authors state different countries and their levels of implementation, however no information or reference is provided for these statements. It would be helpful to explain terms such as "innovators or early adopters", "early majority, "late majority" and "laggard" and why countries have been labeled as such.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the main section, first, the four dimensions previously mentioned in the introduction are addressed, followed by a discussion of additional challenges. It needs to be made clear how these sections are related to each other. A short paragraph on the methodological approach is missing as it is not clear whether these are the findings resulted from conducting interviews and focus groups with different stakeholders (which was mentioned in the last paragraph of the background section). If not, references should be provided on the origin of this information.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the final section, the NRG2Peers roadmap is mentioned. As the roadmap is not specifically described, it is difficult to follow how the roadmap addresses challenges or barriers in the regulation discussed earlier. The roadmap and Advisory App are discussed separately without relating the content to the previous sections. Can these address regulatory barriers?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> All in all, this paper tries to provide an overview of the current regulatory landscape as well as address regulatory barriers that hinder the scale-up of Energy Communities and P2P energy trading markets on the basis of the NRG2PEERs project. However, the article does not follow a clear rationale and misses to tie all sections together and link the findings on barriers with the findings from the NRG2Peer project.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Finally, the article would benefit from a concluding paragraph summarising the findings and providing a lessons learned or recommendations section for addressing regulatory barriers in the future.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The article could make a valuable contribution to highlighting the regulatory barriers to the implementation of ECs. Still, it needs to be revised to improve comprehensibility and highlight benefits of conducting projects such as NRG2PEERS.</p>
