            <p>The scope of the article is highly relevant and it is clear it departs from a robust body of work on the topic of energy communities and P2P.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The article departs in the "background" section from a detailed account of the European context, in terms of regulatory frameworks for the energy transition, leading up to the concept of Renewable Energy Communities, which is very informative and relevant. It also highlights the relevance of peer-to-peer trading in decentralized systems and the role of prosumers and energy communities, which is very clear and offers a coherent background to the article.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> However, while the contents of the article are highly relevant and well referenced, and pertinent to current debates and literature on RECs and P2P, I find the article could benefit from a structure that is more focused on its key findings and more explicit about the research concerns being addressed and the results already attained. This approach would in my view considerably improve the article and its scholarly interest.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> I try to provide below specific comments and some clear examples for the authors to consider:</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> First, in the second to last paragraph of the background section, we read &#x201c;despite the benefits related to both the RECs structure and P2P trading mechanism, these are not extensively implemented in Europe&#x201d;. This sentence nicely sets a problem statement that we hope will be addressed to some extent in the article.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Yet, in what follows, along this paragraph we learn more about what project NRG2PEERS will do to address this problem, rather than gaining a bit more insight into the problem. This is where I think the article could be improved. Rather than focussing on what project NRG2PEERS will bring, would be more interesting to read the key research questions that have already been tackled and early insight into the &#x201c;main barriers for a wide implementation of RECs in Europe&#x201d;.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the same paragraph, for instance, the authors refer there are nine pilots in four EU countries, briefly categorizing them as innovators, late majority, laggards, etc. It would be important to have a brief description of what these categories mean, which also gives us more specific insight into the relevance of looking at these pilots and the key concerns that the project&#x2019;s research is tackling. Thus, clearly framing the article&#x2019;s problem statement.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> On the other hand, the information in this paragraph related to the different other aspects of project NRG2PEERS can be in my view deleted (i.e., sentences from &#x201c;The project fosters the achievement (&#x2026;) to Xu et al.2014), since this information does not add additional inputs to the article&#x2019;s aim, but rather tells us about the project (and the article is not about the project but about regulatory barriers to P2P energy communities in the EU context).</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> As it is now I learn more about the goals of the project than about the specific research questions/concerns that the article is addressing.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> On that note, it would be also good to end the background section by spelling out a clear research concern that the article will tackle &#x2013; e.g., what are the key barriers to the wide implementation of RECs in Europe, and what possible solutions are needed?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The abstract should also be more focused on what the article is bringing and less on describing the project.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Then the following section of the article is very clear in describing the different dimensions for the implementation of EC in Europe. However, this section heading is about &#x2018;barriers&#x2019;, yet the word barriers does not appear in the entire section.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> First, there should be a sentence that clarifies how these dimensions relate to the main barriers &#x2013; is it a framework to map out and identify critical barriers to implementation? Also, the description of the dimensions should include a note on their interactions and on the potential barriers that are derived from these dimensions. For instance, the Market dimension &#x2013; what kind of barriers can be expected and/or have already been identified?&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The description of the dimensions alone does not provide specific insight into the barriers. Then some of the examples provided &#x2013; e.g. Italy, etc. would serve to illustrate the barriers, making a clear connection to them. For instance, &#x00a0;what barrier/s does the Italy example illustrate?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> As it is now, the short accounts from the pilot studies do not provide specific illustrations of specific barriers. In the two last paragraphs of this section, it is not clear if the text is still referring to Italy, or more broadly to problems that are general to all EU countries.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> There is a typo in:&#x201d; Reliable ICT infrastructures o are..&#x201d;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> &#x00a0;Finally, it would be nice to have an accompanying figure illustrating these dimensions, and their interactions.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The last section of the article is centred on what the project NRG2PEERS will bring. Here it would be more relevant to the article if the solutions that are provided by the project are clearly interlinked with the barriers described previously. So the article moves from: 
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Providing a clear question on what the barriers are to implementation</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Offering a summary of key barriers already identified with specific examples from the pilot studies</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>Presenting a set of possible solutions &#x2013; which are to be implemented by the project &#x2013; in a way that makes the reader establish a clear connection with the barriers previously listed.</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list> In the last section, it could be an option to organize the solutions by top-down and bottom-up, rather than by roadmaps and advisory app. This would invert the logic, but also link again to the barriers &#x2013; there are barriers that are mainly at the social/citizens level, and others that are more striking at the top/institutional level. Finally, I&#x2019;m missing a concluding paragraph, that again is more centred on the insights provided by the paper and less on the upcoming events of the project.</p>
            <p> </p>
